{
  "texts": [
    "(66)Each set S i can be understood as a set of t indices/positions of a d length bit string.",
    "For some given bit string y, we use y S i to denote the sub-string of y, of length t, where the elements of y S i are the elements of y at indices S i.Definition 12 (1-bit extractor).",
    "A 1-bit extractor is a strong seeded extractor Ext 1 s: {0, 1} n × {0, 1} d → {0, 1}, i.e.",
    "a strong seeded extractor with output length exactly 1.The ith output bit of the Trevisan extractor, Trevisan(x, y): {0, 1} n ×{0, 1} d → {0, 1} m, can be written as:Trevisan(x, y) i = Ext 1 s (x, y S i) (67)where i ∈ {1,..., m} denotes the ith output bit, S 1,..., S m are the outputs of the weak design.Block weak design: In our implementation, we follow that of [21] and use a (Equation ( 65)) instances of the weak design from Hartman and Raz [61] to form a single block weak design.",
    "Using the Hartman and Raz weak design obliges t to be prime."
  ]
}